{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Contamination has turned up in scores of communities in recent years, and experts cite holes in the safety net of rules and procedures.", "abstract": "Researchers and public health officials warn inadequate coverage of clean-water laws, along with lax enforcement of safety rules and procedures, allow lead and other harmful contaminants into drinking water in cities and communities across United States; efforts to address shortcomings often encounter push-back from industries like agriculture and mining that fear cost increases, and from politicians ideologically opposed to government regulation.", "section_name": "U.S.", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Michael", "role": "reported", "lastname": "WINES", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}, {"firstname": "John", "role": "reported", "lastname": "SCHWARTZ", "rank": 2, "organization": ""}], "original": "By MICHAEL WINES and JOHN SCHWARTZ", "contributor": "Doris Burke and Alain Delaqu\u00e9ri\u00e8re contributed research."}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/09/us/regulatory-gaps-leave-unsafe-lead-levels-in-water-nationwide.html", "lead_paragraph": "Contamination has turned up in scores of communities in recent years, and experts cite holes in the safety net of rules and procedures.", "headline": {"main": "Unsafe Lead Levels in Tap Water Not Limited to Flint", "print_headline": "Holes in Safety Net Let Contaminants in Water"}, "_id": "56b8673c38f0d87ed55e97f2", "word_count": "2239", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/02/06/us/00water-web01/00water-web01-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/02/06/us/00water-web01/00water-web01-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2016/02/06/us/00water-web01/00water-web01-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2016/02/06/us/00water-web01/00water-web01-articleL